04206nam a22005655i 9780300196139DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20082008ctu    fo  d z      eng d  a97803001961397 a10.12987/97803001961392doi  a(DE-B1597)486470  a(OCoLC)1024018930  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  actucUS-CT 4aMT145.B42R67 2002 7aMUS0230302bisacsh04a786.21831 aRosen, Charles, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBeethoven's Piano Sonatas :bA Short Companion /cCharles Rosen. 1aNew Haven, CT : bYale University Press, c[2008] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (272 p.) :bIllustrated throughout with music examples  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of tracks on accompanying CD -- tPreface -- tPART I: The Tradition -- tIntroduction -- tFormal principles -- tPhrasing -- tTempo -- tPedal, trills, extending the keyboard -- tPART II: The Sonatas -- tThe eighteenth-century sonatas -- tYouthful popularity 1800-1802 -- tThe years of mastery -- tThe years of stress -- tThe last sonatas -- tEndnotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBeethoven’s piano sonatas form one of the most important collections of works in the whole history of music. Spanning several decades of his life as a composer, the sonatas soon came to be seen as the first body of substantial serious works for piano suited to performance in large concert halls seating hundreds of people.In this comprehensive and authoritative guide, Charles Rosen places the works in context and provides an understanding of the formal principles involved in interpreting and performing this unique repertoire, covering such aspects as sonata form, phrasing, and tempo, as well as the use of pedal and trills. In the second part of his book, he looks at the sonatas individually, from the earliest works of the 1790s through the sonatas of Beethoven’s youthful popularity of the early 1800s, the subsequent years of mastery, the years of stress (1812-1817), and the last three sonatas of the 1820s.Composed as much for private music-making as public recital, Beethoven’s sonatas have long formed a bridge between the worlds of the salon and the concert hall. For today’s audience, Rosen has written a guide that brings out the gravity, passion, and humor of these works and will enrich the appreciation of a wide range of readers, whether listeners, amateur musicians, or professional pianists.The book includes a CD of Rosen performing extracts from several of the sonatas, illustrating points made in the text.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aSonatas (Piano)xAnalysis, appreciation. 7aMUSIC / Musical Instruments / Piano & Keyboard.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311053799408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook-Package Archive Pre-2000z97831105380140 cprintz978030009070340uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030019613940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300196139423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300196139/original  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-053801-4  Yale University Press eBook-Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY